{
  "texts": [
    "Developing algorithms that selectively forget or protect specific learned behaviors would be necessary in those cases.",
    "Andrychowicz et al. (2017) presented a technique to deal with sparse rewards, one of the significant and challenging problems in Reinforcement learning, because it imposed on the agent to learn long-term policies (until it receives a reward) or to explore an arbitrarily large space of experiences, considering that the immediate rewards are fundamental to guiding the optimal approximation.",
    "Despite impacting all methods of RL in different domains, this is a particular issue when dealing with continuous action spaces in roboticsrelated problems.",
    "According to the authors, a common challenge, especially in robotics, is engineering a reward function that reflects the task and can guide policy optimization.",
    "Many approaches dedicate efforts to formulating complicated cost functions for problems like staking a brick on top of another, which limits the application of RL because it requires domain-specific knowledge."
  ]
}